    "data_flow": "1) Order arrives at Ingress → 2) Assignment Service queries in-memory cache for top ~10 nearby available couriers → 3) Single DB transaction: SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED on best candidate, INSERT assignment, UPDATE courier status → 4) On commit, NOTIFY triggers cache refresh across all service instances → 5) Response returned to caller with courier_id. Total budget: ~20ms network + ~30ms cache filter + ~50ms DB transaction + ~20ms response = ~120ms typical, well within 200ms.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Pessimistic Locking (SELECT FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED)",
        "rationale": "SKIP LOCKED is the critical detail. If two concurrent assignment requests target the same courier, one acquires the lock and proceeds; the other SKIPS that row and picks the next-best candidate. This eliminates deadlocks, prevents double-assignment, and avoids retry storms — all in a single round-trip. This is PostgreSQL's killer feature for exactly this class of problem."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Single-Leader Writes with Synchronous Replication",
        "rationale": "Guarantees strong consistency (all writes go through one node with row-level locking) while providing durability and fast failover. Synchronous replication means zero data loss on leader failure. The 5-15 second failover window is the availability trade-off — acceptable given the alternative (double-assigned couriers) is a business-critical failure."
